				<title>(no title)</title>
				<link>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-4104546/scp-3460#post-3622282</link>
				<description></description>
				<pubDate>Mon, 30 Oct 2017 02:03:51 +0000</pubDate>
				<wikidot:authorName>Abettik</wikidot:authorName>				<wikidot:authorUserId>1700758</wikidot:authorUserId>				<content:encoded>
					<![CDATA[
						 <p>-1</p> <p>Found this quite boring, and uninteresting.</p> <div class="collapsible-block"> <div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">+&nbsp;Show</a></div> <div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none"> <div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">-&nbsp;Hide</a></div> <div class="collapsible-block-content"> <p>I also found the description clunky and confusing, and didn't really understand it until the first log. I actually STILL don't understand what the needles measure on their own, if you just leave them and watch. Then, the logs were generally repetitive, until the last one, where it almost seemed like a narrative &quot;solution in search of a problem,&quot; so to speak. I guess what I'm trying to say there is that while I could see the potential in how it -could- be used, the document didn't organically get me to care. Maybe if you had delved deeper into the person trying to keep their stalker/ex away&#8230; or gone into why it was created (maybe a guy trying to create a run-in with some girl), or made it a bit more interesting on its own, I could upvote in good faith.</p> </div> </div> </div> 
				 	]]>
				</content:encoded>							</item>
